President Obama announced his intent to nominate Francis S. Collins as the Director of the National Institutes of Health (NIH). Collins is a renowned physician-geneticist known for his groundbreaking work in discovering disease genes and leading the Human Genome Project. He served as the Director of the National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI) from 1993-2008, where he successfully completed the project ahead of schedule and under budget. Collins has also made significant contributions to scientific research, discovering genes responsible for various diseases such as cystic fibrosis, neurofibromatosis, and Huntington's disease. He has a strong interest in the intersection of science and faith and has written books on the subject. Collins holds degrees in Chemistry, Physical Chemistry, and Medicine. He has been recognized with prestigious honors and awards, including the Presidential Medal of Freedom.